<subSubSection id="C32C9FECA96CAD1D0F8EFD62765DD995" pageId="2" pageNumber="801" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B89CC67A96CAD1D0F8EFD62765DD995" blockId="2.[736,1324,675,1097]" lastBlockId="2.[120,1325,1103,3455]" pageId="2" pageNumber="801">
It appears from genetic studies that Giraffes fall into three groups: West African Giraffes (peralta); North African Giraffes (antiguorum, 
<taxonomicName id="4C36B7E4A96CAD1D0ECAFCE47336DEAE" box="[933,1051,875,900]" class="Mammalia" family="Giraffidae" genus="Giraffa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Artiodactyla" pageId="2" pageNumber="801" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulata">reticulata</taxonomicName>
, rothschildi, thornicrofti, and probably 
<taxonomicName id="4C36B7E4A96CAD1D097CFC0573FEDE81" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1043,1235,906,939]" class="Mammalia" family="Giraffidae" genus="Giraffa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Artiodactyla" pageId="2" pageNumber="801" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="camelopardalis">camelopardalis</taxonomicName>
); and southern African Giraffes (angolensis and guraffa). The “Masai Giraffe,” 
<taxonomicName id="4C36B7E4A96CAD1D09FFFC567209DED0" box="[1168,1316,985,1018]" class="Mammalia" family="Giraffidae" genus="Giraffa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Artiodactyla" pageId="2" pageNumber="801" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tippelskirchi">tippelskirchi</taxonomicName>
, exhibits similarities with both the southern and the northern groups. Genetic differences, ranging from 0-15% to 6-9%, are below those required for the establishment of distinct species. Nine regional variants are currently recognized as subspecies, all of which interbreed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
